snippet.textDisplay:
Allow me to take a contrarian view of this. I think this fusion is beautiful. It adds to the power of the Mahishasura Maradani Stotram. The Hindi interlude could be taken as an expression of intense love (or devotion) to the Goddess.

All in all, this is a lovely rendition of the Stotram. I understand where the emotions of the purists are coming from, but I must gently disagree with them on this.

snippet.textDisplay: To all ye haters of this divine song.... Please read the description... The part sung by Sona is a wonderful composition of Bulle Shah.... Sufism And Sanskrit... A never heard Gorgeous Combo!!! I pray you understand that in Sufism, an invocation to God is similar to that to a mortal beloved... 'Tere Ishq Nachaya' for me is as synonymous to Meera's or Chaitanya Mahaprabhu's dance for Krishna as it is for Heer dancing for Ranjha... 'Jaldi aaja ve...' is not desecration... It's a call for God to come running to us.... And to summarize, Hinduism is not a fanatic religion... It's a way of life that assimilates the best of everything & in this case, makes it outstanding... Bulle Shah's Poetry invokes the Divine ("Durga") with a passion SIMILAR to the Stotram. Namaste.
